Posted: Sat Aug 18, 2012 5:26 am
Lawn bowls, I think they're called. Generally you have two teams, of one or a few people each. You have a jack (smaller, white ball) that is rolled to one end of a flat, very finely trimmed bit of lawn. Then each team takes turns to roll these large black balls (smooth surface, somewhat heavy - half marked with a red dot, half with a blue dot) towards the jack. They're weighted slightly where the coloured dot is.Aim is at the end of the game (when you've gone through all your bowling balls - usually have 6 per team maybe) to have the most balls near the jack - for pro games they may well add up all the distances and do sums, think I've seen this on tv.Tactics include hitting (well, gently moving is the idea) the jack, knocking other team's balls away, block bowling paths that will allow other team to get easily get good positioning/points, etc. (Due to the weighted part the bowl will curl in when it runs low on momentum and has been rolled with the weight to one side. You can just roll it straight with the weighted bit on a top-down axis and blast everyone's out of the way. I believe this isn't considered good form in the league games popular amongst the older generations who seem to favour lawn bowls, though.)Think that's it, anyhow. Had a mini indoor set when I was a kid - mostly to stop us trying to play pétanque by flinging metal balls around near things made of glass. -c-
