DrPizza wrote:Control Group wrote:DrPizza wrote:Quote:The hitch is that they can't sell the property, because it's illegal for them to evict the tenants. They can ask the tenants to leave at the end of the next lease cycle (so 18 months from now), but the tenants don't have to.Why not?Getting this secondhand, I don't know the specific laws involved. My coworker's solicitors* have indicated that rent control laws (a term I'm using not because it's how they are actually terms, but because their intent seems to be the same as US rent control laws) prohibit eviction and rent increase per the limits I mentioned.I am struggling to see how that could be, particularly as you say it's being used for office space, and not a dwelling. I suppose it might be due to unusual stipulations of their specific contract, but I don't believe there's any law that could create such a situation.I just sent out an IM to my coworker to find out what the specific law is, but I know one of the problems is that they don't want to evict in order to live there, they want to evict in order to sell. If one of the surviving members of the family wanted to take the space as primary residence, they'd be able to evict.
